The {{/opt/bamboo-elastic-agent/bin/restoreEbsSnapshotFromUserData.sh}} has the following line in it:
{code}
. /etc/profile.d/aws-apitools-common.sh
{code}
Which is useful if you are using an Amazon Linux AMI, however, it fails if not.

It should be:
{code}
[ -f /etc/profile.d/aws-apitools-common.sh ] && . /etc/profile.d/aws-apitools-common.sh
{code}

Steps to reproduce:

1) create plan, script task:
{noformat}
echo $bamboo_buildResultKey
echo $bamboo_buildNumber
{noformat}
2) run the plan
3a) expected result (in the logs) is to see something like
{noformat}
PROJ-PLAN-JOB1-1
1
{noformat}
3b) while current behavior is:
{noformat}


{noformat}
(these environment variables are undefined, that's why we see empty logs)

Seems we pass the plan/global variables into the environment:
* [https://bitbucket.org/atlassian/bamboo/annotate/949eea7f1933/components/bamboo-core/src/main/java/com/atlassian/bamboo/process/EnvironmentVariableAccessorImpl.java#line-80]

But we don't do that for built-in variables like:
* ${bamboo.buildPlanName}
* ${bamboo.buildKey}
* ${bamboo.buildNumber}
* ${bamboo.buildResultKey}
* ${bamboo.buildTimeStamp}
* ${bamboo.repository.revision.number}
* ${bamboo.build.working.directory}
etc...

The REST CALL to retrieve the build results for a specific plan in a project is always zero if the URL goes down all the way to the JOB level. If however the URL is stopped at the plan level, then the jiraIssues tag gives the correct number of issues associated to the builds together with their issue keys. We can either make it functional or remove it from the tag if it is not useful at the job level. Here are some exmaples:

http://<URL>/rest/api/latest/result/PROJECT-BUILDKEY?expand=results.result.jiraIssues {color:green}WORKING{color}

http://<URL>/rest/api/latest/result/PROJECT-BUILDKEY-JOB1-6?expand=results.result.jiraIssues {color:red}NOT WORKING{color}

The "buildForceCleanCheckout" build variable stopped working:
{code}
${bamboo.buildForceCleanCheckout}: bad substitution
{code}

How to reproduce: any usage of the variable will fail in the substitution stage

Customer scenario
{quote}

Here is an example situation we see many times:
{noformat}
project build 1.0 runs sanity-test on agent a and connects to lab machine x
    project build 1.1 runs sanity-test on agent b and connects to lab machine x
    project build 2.0 runs sanity-test on agent c and connects to lab machine x
{noformat}

But...and this is the critical part, "lab machine x" can only be accessed by exactly one build plan at a time.

{quote}

Using Bamboo 4.1, on JDK 6, on Windows 7.

I wrote a Bamboo Event Listener that  implements HibernateEventListener and has a getHandledEventClasses and handle methods like so : 

    @Override
    public Class[] getHandledEventClasses() {
        return new Class[]{
         PlanFavouriteAddedEvent.class, PlanFavouriteRemovedEvent.class
                };
    }

    @Override
    public void handleEvent(Event event) {
          log.info(event.getClass().getCanonicalName());
    }


I installed the listener as part of a plugin into Bamboo 4.1. Then i went to several plans and marked them as favourites and then unmarked then as a favourite.

When I clicked to mark a Plan as a favourite (the Star turns gold) and seems to work fine. However in the log is shows : 

com.atlassian.bamboo.event.PlanFavouriteRemovedEvent

which seems to be the REMOVED event.

In the user interface I click the button to turn off the plan being a favourite (the star turns back to grey) and in the log the opposite Event is triggered in the log : 

com.atlassian.bamboo.event.PlanFavouriteAddedEvent


It seems the 2 events got reversed?
